Constructor Flow in Inheritance (C++)

Rule (Most Important)
When a child object is created:

Parent Constructor → Child Constructor

Reason: The child object contains the parent part, so the parent must be initialized first.

Example 1: Single Inheritance
class Person {
public:
    Person() {
        cout << "Person Constructor\n";
    }
};

class Student : public Person {
public:
    Student() {
        cout << "Student Constructor\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Student s;
}
Output
Person Constructor
Student Constructor
Flow
Create Student Object
        ↓
Call Person Constructor
        ↓
Call Student Constructor
        ↓
Object Ready
Memory View
Student Object
------------------
Person Part
------------------
Student Part
------------------

Since the object contains the Person part, C++ initializes it first.

Parameterized Parent Constructor
class Person {
public:
    Person(string name) {
        cout << name;
    }
};

class Student : public Person {
public:
    Student() : Person("Yash") {
    }
};
Syntax
Student() : Person("Yash")

This is called the Initializer List.

Java Equivalent
super("Yash");
Wrong Way ❌
Student() {

    Person("Yash");

}

This creates a temporary Person object, not the parent part of Student.

Always use:

Student() : Person("Yash")
